## What is SAN?

**SAN** stands for **Subject Alternative Name**.

It is a field inside an SSL/TLS certificate that lists **all the domain names the certificate is valid for**.

---

## Why SAN Exists

Originally, certificates only had:

```
CN (Common Name) = example.com
```

But that allows only one domain.

Modern websites often need:

* example.com
* [www.example.com](http://www.example.com)
* api.example.com
* shop.example.com

So SAN was introduced to support multiple domains in one certificate.

---

## 🔐 Example Certificate

```
Subject: CN=example.com

X509v3 Subject Alternative Name:
DNS:example.com
DNS:www.example.com
DNS:api.example.com
```

Now the certificate is valid for all three.

---

## 🚨 How Browsers Use SAN

Modern browsers:

✔ Ignore Common Name for validation
✔ Validate against SAN only

If the domain you visit is **not inside SAN**, you get:

```
NET::ERR_CERT_COMMON_NAME_INVALID
```

Even if CN matches.

---

## 🧠 Example Scenarios

### ✅ Works

Certificate SAN contains:

```
DNS:example.com
DNS:www.example.com
```

User visits:

```
https://www.example.com
```

✔ Valid

---

### ❌ Fails

Certificate SAN contains:

```
DNS:example.com
```

User visits:

```
https://api.example.com
```

🚫 Not listed → certificate error

---

## 🛠 How to Check SAN

```bash
openssl s_client -connect example.com:443 -servername example.com
```

Then look for:

```
X509v3 Subject Alternative Name:
```

---

## 🔎 Types of SAN Entries

SAN can include:

* DNS names → `DNS:example.com`
* Wildcards → `DNS:*.example.com`
* IP addresses → `IP:192.168.1.1`
* Email addresses (rare)

---

## 🌍 Real-World Example

If using:

* A CDN like Cloudflare
* A reverse proxy (Nginx, HAProxy)
* A load balancer

The certificate must include every hostname users might request.

Otherwise, some users get certificate warnings.

---

## 🎯 Memory Trick

Think:

> **CN = Main domain**
> **SAN = Full guest list**

If your domain isn’t on the guest list → you’re not allowed in.

